const islamicPhilosophy:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','A creative tradition of reasoned inquiry',[
    'Islamic philosophy names many philosophical conversations conducted in societies shaped by Islam, often in Arabic but also in Persian and other languages, by Muslim, Christian, Jewish, and other thinkers. It includes falsafa, the disciplined pursuit of philosophical sciences associated with Greek inheritances, but it is not exhausted by falsafa. Kalam theologians developed arguments about divine attributes, freedom, causation, and moral value; jurists analyzed language and reasoning; physicians and astronomers investigated nature; and mystical philosophers joined metaphysics to practices of transformation. The tradition is therefore neither one doctrine nor a religious appendix to Greek philosophy. Its central question is how rigorous inquiry can understand reality, knowledge, human flourishing, and revelation within changing intellectual communities.',
    'Translation was indispensable, yet the familiar story that Islamic thinkers merely preserved Greek books is historically and philosophically false. Translators, patrons, and scholars selected texts, created technical vocabularies, corrected sources, combined Aristotelian and Neoplatonic materials, and posed questions not settled by their inheritances. Al-Kindi argued for philosophy in an Arabic-Islamic setting; al-Farabi reorganized logic, science, politics, and prophecy; Avicenna built a new metaphysical system around essence, existence, and necessary being. Their work became a starting point for criticism and reconstruction across Islamic, Jewish, and Latin traditions. Islamic philosophy is best approached as an evolving argument whose participants transformed both inherited philosophy and the religious, scientific, and political questions of their own worlds.'
  ],['islamic-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','metaphysics'],['al-kindi','al-farabi','avicenna'],['On First Philosophy','The Virtuous City','The Healing']),
  section('historical-development','Translation, system building, critique, and continuation',[
    'From the eighth through tenth centuries, translation movements centered especially in Abbasid Baghdad made works of Aristotle, commentators, medicine, mathematics, and other sciences available in Arabic. Many translators were Syriac-speaking Christians working within multilingual scholarly networks. Al-Kindi used these resources to defend philosophical inquiry and develop arguments about first philosophy, intellect, and the finitude of the world. Al-Farabi produced influential accounts of logic and the classification of sciences while connecting political order to human perfection and prophecy. This period was not a passive reception stage: it created a philosophical language and an institutional ecology in which new systems could be built, criticized, and taught.',
    'Avicenna became the decisive system-builder of the eastern tradition, reshaping logic, psychology, natural philosophy, and metaphysics. Al-Ghazali later criticized a defined set of philosophical theses while adopting logic and engaging Avicennian arguments at a high level; he did not simply end philosophy. In al-Andalus, Ibn Tufayl explored self-directed knowledge in a philosophical narrative, while Averroes defended demonstration and wrote major Aristotelian commentaries. After the twelfth century, philosophical inquiry continued through Avicennian theology, logic, Illuminationism associated with Suhrawardi, and later syntheses such as Mulla Sadra’s. Restricting the story to a classical rise and sudden decline erases centuries of post-classical debate across seminaries, courts, philosophical schools, and commentary traditions.'
  ],['medieval-scholasticism','aristotelianism','neoplatonism'],['al-kindi','al-farabi','avicenna','al-ghazali','ibn-tufayl','averroes','suhrawardi','mulla-sadra'],['The Incoherence of the Philosophers','Hayy ibn Yaqzan','The Decisive Treatise']),
  section('key-concepts','Necessary being, intellect, prophecy, and illumination',[
    'Avicenna distinguishes what a thing is from the fact that it exists. A contingent essence does not contain the sufficient reason for its own existence, so the ordered dependence of contingent beings points toward a necessary existent. This is not merely a borrowed cosmological proof; it belongs to a systematic account of causation, modality, divine simplicity, and emanation. The human intellect likewise becomes a major field of dispute. Philosophers ask how potential understanding becomes actual, how universals are known, whether intellect is individual or shared, and how rational knowledge relates to imagination and embodied perception. Averroes’ views on intellect later generated intense debate in Jewish and Latin philosophy as well as within Islamic traditions.',
    'Prophecy and revelation were philosophically analyzed rather than placed outside reason. Al-Farabi and Avicenna connect prophetic imagination to intelligible truth and political guidance, while theologians contest whether this account adequately preserves divine freedom and the authority of revelation. Kalam arguments about atomism, occasionalism, created acts, and divine attributes create alternative pictures of nature and agency. Suhrawardi’s illuminationist philosophy reorganizes knowledge around presence and light while still engaging logic and demonstration. Mulla Sadra later argues for the primacy of existence, substantial motion, and a dynamic metaphysics of the soul. These concepts show a tradition producing its own problem-spaces rather than merely commenting on foreign texts.'
  ],['metaphysics','epistemology','philosophy-of-mind'],['avicenna','averroes','suhrawardi','mulla-sadra'],['The Salvation','Philosophy of Illumination']),
  section('figures-works','Major figures and works in a connected conversation',[
    'Al-Kindi’s On First Philosophy argues that receiving truth from earlier peoples does not diminish its value and develops a first-cause metaphysics in a new setting. Al-Farabi’s Enumeration of the Sciences and Virtuous City link logical education, political community, prophecy, and happiness. Avicenna’s Book of Healing is an encyclopedia of philosophical sciences rather than a medical book; its Metaphysics and Psychology became especially influential. Al-Ghazali’s Intentions of the Philosophers presents philosophical positions before the Incoherence criticizes selected claims about eternity, divine knowledge, and resurrection. Reading those works together prevents the misleading portrait of a theologian attacking a subject he neither understood nor used.',
    'Ibn Tufayl’s Hayy ibn Yaqzan dramatizes a person developing knowledge through observation, reason, and contemplation outside ordinary society. Averroes’ Decisive Treatise relates philosophy to revealed law, while his commentaries reconstruct Aristotle and defend demonstrative inquiry. Suhrawardi’s Philosophy of Illumination combines rigorous logical preparation with a metaphysics of lights and knowledge by presence. Mulla Sadra’s Transcendent Philosophy integrates Avicennian, illuminationist, theological, and mystical inheritances while transforming them through the primacy of existence and substantial motion. No short canon captures every region or genre, but these works display sustained originality across logic, metaphysics, psychology, politics, theology, narrative, and spiritual practice.'
  ],['logic','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion'],['al-kindi','al-farabi','avicenna','al-ghazali','ibn-tufayl','averroes','suhrawardi','mulla-sadra'],['On First Philosophy','The Virtuous City','The Healing','The Incoherence of the Philosophers','Hayy ibn Yaqzan','The Decisive Treatise']),
  section('internal-debates','Demonstration, revelation, causation, and the good life',[
    'One central debate concerns the reach of demonstration. Philosophers often distinguish demonstrative knowledge from dialectical or rhetorical persuasion, while asking how revealed texts should be interpreted when a sound argument appears to conflict with a literal reading. Averroes assigns methods to different intellectual capacities and defends interpretation under disciplined conditions; al-Ghazali argues that philosophers failed to demonstrate several contested metaphysical conclusions. The disagreement is not a simple battle between reason and faith. It concerns what counts as demonstration, which claims revelation makes, who may interpret them, and how philosophical education relates to a religious and political community.',
    'Causation produces another family of disputes. Avicennian accounts give created causes real explanatory roles within an ordered dependence on the necessary existent. Occasionalist approaches emphasize that God, rather than created things acting independently, brings events about; al-Ghazali’s famous fire-and-cotton discussion challenges claims of necessary connection without denying regular experience. Thinkers also dispute divine attributes, freedom, moral value, the eternity or origination of the world, bodily resurrection, the unity of intellect, and whether philosophical contemplation or revealed law best guides flourishing. Internal variety is not evidence that the tradition lacks identity. It is the historical substance of the tradition.'
  ],['philosophy-of-religion','philosophy-of-science','ethics'],['avicenna','al-ghazali','averroes'],['The Incoherence of the Philosophers','The Incoherence of the Incoherence']),
  section('neighbors','Relations to theology, science, politics, and other traditions',[
    'Islamic philosophy overlaps with philosophy of religion but should not be reduced to arguments about God. Logic, medicine, optics, astronomy, mathematics, psychology, language, ethics, and political philosophy were connected parts of intellectual life. The boundaries among falsafa, kalam, jurisprudence, Sufism, and scientific inquiry were contested and porous. Al-Farabi’s political thought draws on Plato while addressing prophecy and law; Avicenna’s medical and psychological work interacts with his metaphysics; al-Ghazali combines legal, theological, philosophical, and spiritual disciplines. Modern categories help organize the atlas, but they should not be projected backward as sealed departments.',
    'The tradition also belongs to a wider history of transmission. Jewish thinkers including Maimonides wrote within the Arabic intellectual world; Latin scholastics encountered translated works by Avicenna and Averroes; later Persian traditions developed questions less visible in standard European narratives. Aristotelianism and Neoplatonism are genuine neighbors, yet Islamic philosophers combined and revised them rather than choosing between fixed schools. Connections to medieval scholasticism should therefore run in several directions: translated arguments changed Latin philosophy, and the comparison reveals distinct institutions and theological commitments rather than one civilization handing a torch to another.'
  ],['logic','political-philosophy','philosophy-of-science','medieval-scholasticism'],['al-farabi','avicenna','maimonides','aquinas','averroes'],['Guide for the Perplexed','Summa Theologiae']),
  section('misunderstandings','Misconceptions that erase philosophical creativity',[
    'The first misunderstanding is that Islamic philosophy merely preserved Greek philosophy until Europe was ready to recover it. Translation mattered, but translation itself required interpretation, and the resulting systems introduced new distinctions, arguments, and disciplines. Avicenna is not a warehouse for Aristotle; his metaphysics redirected later Islamic, Jewish, and Christian thought. A second mistake is that al-Ghazali destroyed philosophy. His criticism targeted particular conclusions, employed philosophical tools, and helped reorganize later debates. A third is that Averroes represents the whole tradition. His commentaries were enormously important in Latin reception, but Avicennian and post-Avicennian traditions often had a deeper continuing presence in Islamic intellectual settings.',
    'It is also misleading to treat reason and revelation as two armies or to identify philosophy with secular unbelief. Participants held different views about prophecy, interpretation, and demonstration while working within religiously structured societies. Mystical philosophy is not simply an irrational rejection of argument: Suhrawardi and Mulla Sadra integrate demonstration with accounts of presence and transformation, even if their methods remain contestable. Finally, “Islamic” does not mean that every contributor was Muslim or that one essence unifies every region and century. The label marks overlapping languages, institutions, problems, and inheritances whose diversity must remain visible.'
  ],['islamic-philosophy','medieval-scholasticism'],['al-ghazali','averroes','avicenna'],[]),
  section('modern-relevance','Why the tradition matters now',[
    'Islamic philosophy changes the map of philosophy. It reveals that problems often taught as exclusively European—modality, intentionality, the relation of essence and existence, skepticism about causation, theories of intellect, and political education—were developed through multilingual exchanges. This matters for contemporary curricula and for public accounts of intellectual history. A connected history is not a ceremonial gesture toward inclusion; it explains why Aquinas responds to Avicenna, why early modern discussions inherit scholastic distinctions, and why later philosophy in Islamic societies cannot be understood through a narrative that ends in the twelfth century.',
    'Its substantive questions also remain live. Debates about religious interpretation and public reason concern who has authority to interpret and what standards can be shared. Accounts of dependence and necessary existence inform contemporary metaphysics and philosophy of religion. Theories of intellect and imagination illuminate disputes about cognition, artificial intelligence, and the social role of expertise. Philosophical approaches to illumination and self-transformation invite comparison with phenomenology while requiring care about different aims. The tradition offers resources for thinking, not ready-made cultural answers, and its internal disagreements model how inherited authorities can be critically transformed.'
  ],['political-philosophy','philosophy-of-mind','phenomenology'],['avicenna','al-farabi','mulla-sadra'],[]),
  section('reading-path','Where to begin and how to continue',[
    'Begin with al-Kindi’s compact On First Philosophy and selections from al-Farabi on the sciences or the virtuous city. Then read Avicenna on essence, existence, and necessary being with a guide that explains his logical and metaphysical vocabulary. Pair al-Ghazali’s autobiographical Deliverance from Error with selected discussions from the Incoherence so that his spiritual and critical projects are not collapsed. Averroes’ Decisive Treatise provides an accessible route into demonstration, law, and interpretation. Ibn Tufayl’s Hayy ibn Yaqzan offers a literary entry into knowledge, nature, solitude, and community.',
    'Where possible, compare translations and note whether a modern edition presents a complete work, selected chapters, or later reports. Many technical terms carry histories that no single English equivalent captures. Reading slowly across a small argumentative sequence is more reliable than collecting isolated claims about an entire civilization.',
    'Continue by following one argument across thinkers: necessary existence from Avicenna into Maimonides and Aquinas; causation from Avicenna to al-Ghazali and Averroes; or intellect from Aristotle through al-Farabi, Avicenna, and Averroes. Advanced readers can then approach Suhrawardi and Mulla Sadra with scholarship attentive to their post-classical settings. Keep separate notes on philosophical claims, institutional context, and later reception. This prevents Latin influence from becoming the measure of importance and makes it possible to see both shared problems and transformations within Islamic intellectual history.'
  ],['islamic-philosophy','aristotelianism','philosophy-of-religion'],['al-kindi','al-farabi','avicenna','al-ghazali','ibn-tufayl','averroes','suhrawardi','mulla-sadra'],['On First Philosophy','The Virtuous City','The Healing','Deliverance from Error','The Decisive Treatise','Hayy ibn Yaqzan'])
];

const rationalism:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','Reason, experience, and the architecture of knowledge',[
    'Rationalism is a retrospective label for early modern projects that assign reason an especially important role in explaining knowledge, concepts, and reality. Descartes, Spinoza, and Leibniz are conventionally grouped as continental rationalists, but they did not announce one shared platform and they disagree about substance, freedom, mind, God, and method. Each uses experience, and none believes that a person can learn every fact by thinking in isolation. The organizing question is narrower and more demanding: are there significant principles, concepts, or forms of knowledge whose warrant cannot be derived from sense experience alone, and what must reality be like for reason to grasp them?',
    'The label becomes useful when it identifies arguments rather than stereotypes. Rationalists appeal to innate ideas or capacities, a priori principles, deduction, mathematics, and explanatory demands such as sufficient reason. Yet observation remains necessary for ordinary history, natural inquiry, and the application of general principles. Their empiricist critics likewise reason extensively and accept more than raw sensation. The dispute concerns the sources, limits, and structure of justification: whether experience supplies all conceptual content, whether necessity can be known from particular cases, and whether intelligible order belongs to reality or only to our habits of thought. Kant later transforms this dispute rather than simply selecting one side.'
  ],['epistemology','empiricism','metaphysics'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','kant'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Ethics','Monadology']),
  section('historical-development','From scholastic inheritance to critical philosophy',[
    'Seventeenth-century rationalism developed amid religious conflict, new mathematical sciences, mechanical philosophy, and continuing scholastic education. Descartes sought a method capable of resisting inherited error and grounding the sciences, but his concepts of substance, causation, and God also respond to medieval debates. In the Meditations, doubt clears away beliefs that can be questioned so that the activity of thinking becomes certain. The later reconstruction of knowledge depends on arguments about clear and distinct perception, divine nondeception, and the existence of bodies. Cartesian rationalism is therefore not just the cogito; it is an ambitious, contested route from first-person certainty to metaphysics and natural philosophy.',
    'Spinoza transforms Cartesian vocabulary into a monism in which God or Nature is the one substance and finite things are modes. Leibniz instead argues for a plurality of simple substances, pre-established harmony, and a world selected through divine wisdom. Anne Conway, often excluded from the standard roster, criticizes Cartesian dualism and develops a vitalist metaphysics of created substance. Rationalist debates spread through correspondence, scientific academies, religious communities, and arguments over freedom and toleration. Locke, Berkeley, and Hume challenge accounts of innate content and necessary connection; Kant argues that experience supplies matter while a priori forms and categories make objective experience possible. The familiar opposition thus culminates in a critical reorganization, not a victory score.'
  ],['medieval-scholasticism','philosophy-of-science','german-idealism'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway','locke','hume','kant'],['Principles of Philosophy','A Treatise Concerning the Principles of Human Knowledge','Critique of Pure Reason']),
  section('key-concepts','Innateness, a priori knowledge, deduction, and sufficient reason',[
    'Innateness does not always mean a fully formed sentence present in an infant mind. It can describe dispositions, structural capacities, or concepts whose content cannot be assembled from sensory impressions alone. Descartes appeals to the idea of an infinite and perfect being; Leibniz compares the mind to veined marble whose structure guides what experience can bring forth. A priori knowledge is justified independently of particular sensory evidence, as in logic or mathematics, though experience may prompt a person to recognize it. Rationalists disagree about which truths have this status and how finite minds gain access to them.',
    'Deductive or geometrical order promises more than tidy presentation. Spinoza’s Ethics seeks to show how claims about substance, mind, emotion, bondage, and freedom follow within one explanatory system. The principle of sufficient reason, strongly associated with Leibniz, requires that there be an adequate explanation for why something is so rather than otherwise. Descartes’ clear and distinct perception, Spinoza’s adequate ideas, and Leibniz’s distinction between truths of reason and truths of fact offer different standards of intelligibility. These concepts create pressure: if reason demands complete explanation, how can contingency, individuality, error, and freedom remain genuine?'
  ],['logic','metaphysics','epistemology'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz'],['Discourse on Method','Ethics','New Essays on Human Understanding']),
  section('figures-works','Descartes, Spinoza, Leibniz, Conway, and their arguments',[
    'Descartes’ Discourse and Meditations introduce methodic doubt, the cogito, mind-body distinction, and arguments for God, while the Principles embeds these themes in a broader account of nature. Spinoza’s Ethics begins from definitions and axioms but aims at a practical transformation: understanding necessity can loosen passive emotions and produce a freer, more active life. His Theological-Political Treatise defends interpretive and political freedoms while separating philosophical inquiry from claims of clerical authority. Treating rationalism as purely abstract epistemology misses its ethical and political ambitions.',
    'Leibniz’s Discourse on Metaphysics, Monadology, New Essays, and correspondence develop possible worlds, sufficient reason, identity, perception, and harmony. His arguments often arise through exchange with critics rather than a single definitive system. Anne Conway’s Principles of the Most Ancient and Modern Philosophy challenges sharp mind-body dualism through a hierarchy of living created substance and deserves a place in the conversation rather than as a decorative exception. Malebranche and others broaden the field further, though they lack atlas records. The major works should be compared problem by problem, because the three canonical rationalists frequently share vocabulary while giving incompatible accounts of its meaning.'
  ],['philosophy-of-mind','ethics','political-philosophy'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway'],['Meditations on First Philosophy','Ethics','Monadology','The Principles of the Most Ancient and Modern Philosophy']),
  section('internal-debates','Substance, freedom, mind, and the limits of explanation',[
    'Rationalists divide sharply over substance. Descartes recognizes thinking and extended created substances dependent on God, producing the problem of how mind and body interact. Spinoza argues that thought and extension are attributes of one substance, dissolving interaction at the cost of ordinary pictures of individual independence. Leibniz proposes a plurality of nonextended monads whose coordinated states do not causally interact in the usual sense. Conway rejects inert matter and Cartesian dualism through a vital continuum. These alternatives show why “reason over experience” cannot define the movement: their deepest dispute concerns what kinds of beings and relations can make experience intelligible.',
    'Freedom is equally contested. Descartes connects will to judgment and divine creation; Spinoza denies uncaused choice while redefining freedom as acting from adequate understanding of one’s nature; Leibniz tries to reconcile sufficient reason, divine foreknowledge, contingency, and responsibility. Rationalists also dispute whether ideas represent objects directly, how error is possible under a perfect creator, whether evil is compatible with providence, and how mathematics relates to physical reality. Their systems seek unity, but the demand for unity repeatedly threatens to flatten contingency or embodiment. Internal criticism is therefore part of rationalism’s method, not evidence that the label has no use.'
  ],['philosophy-of-mind','philosophy-of-religion','ethics'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway'],['Theodicy','Ethics']),
  section('neighbors','Empiricism, science, scholasticism, and idealism',[
    'Empiricism is rationalism’s most familiar neighbor, but the border is porous. Locke criticizes innate principles while accepting demonstrative knowledge in suitable domains. Berkeley reasons from the contents of perception toward immaterialism. Hume uses exact argument to limit claims about causation, self, and necessity. Rationalists themselves appeal to experiments and scientific findings. The productive contrast concerns what sensory evidence can explain: whether experience can yield necessity and universality, whether concepts arise by abstraction, and whether knowledge requires principles contributed by the mind. Reading paired problems is more accurate than placing thinkers on a reason-versus-senses line.',
    'Medieval scholasticism supplies vocabulary and arguments that early modern writers revise even while presenting themselves as reformers. Philosophy of science appears in disputes about mechanism, laws, mathematics, hypothesis, and experiment. Philosophy of religion is inseparable from accounts of divine perfection and creation, though Spinoza radically changes what “God” means. German Idealism inherits Kant’s transformation of the rationalist-empiricist dispute and renews the problem of how thought is answerable to reality. Analytic philosophy later revisits a priori knowledge, modality, and sufficient reason without simply restoring seventeenth-century systems.'
  ],['empiricism','philosophy-of-science','medieval-scholasticism','german-idealism'],['locke','berkeley','hume','kant'],['An Essay Concerning Human Understanding','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
  section('misunderstandings','Why rationalism is not reason without experience',[
    'The central misconception is that rationalists reject the senses and believe all facts can be deduced from the armchair. Descartes conducts scientific investigations, Leibniz studies empirical discoveries, and rationalist systems require experience to determine many contingent truths. Their claim is that experience alone cannot account for every concept or warrant, especially necessity, universality, and the principles organizing inquiry. A second misconception is that rationalists all defend the same innate ideas. Descartes, Spinoza, Leibniz, and Conway build importantly different models of mind, development, and intelligibility.',
    'It is also misleading to equate rationalism with being rational or empiricism with being evidence-based. Those honorific uses turn historical categories into praise and criticism. Geometrical presentation does not guarantee that premises are true, while a difficult metaphysical system can still be motivated by concrete problems. Finally, rationalism is not exhausted by three isolated male geniuses. Correspondence, critics, theological controversies, scientific institutions, and thinkers such as Conway shaped the debate. The label should organize comparisons, not hide networks or convert a later textbook category into a party membership card.'
  ],['rationalism','empiricism'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway'],[]),
  section('modern-relevance','A priori structure in mathematics, mind, and technology',[
    'Rationalist questions survive wherever knowledge appears to outrun accumulated observations. Mathematics, logic, modality, language acquisition, and theories of cognitive structure raise disputes about whether learning presupposes built-in capacities or organizing principles. Contemporary positions need not accept Cartesian innate ideas to inherit this pressure. Artificial intelligence makes it practical: can generalization emerge from training data alone, what architectures constrain learning, and does successful prediction amount to understanding? Rationalism offers no automatic answer, but it insists that inputs become knowledge only within a structure capable of representing relations and reasons.',
    'The demand for sufficient explanation also shapes metaphysics and science. Researchers ask why laws hold, why parameters take their values, and when a model explains rather than merely fits. Yet rationalist history warns that a demand for total intelligibility can outrun evidence or erase contingency. Spinoza’s analysis of emotion and freedom, Conway’s vitalist critique of dualism, and Leibniz’s relational ideas remain resources in ethics, mind, and systems theory. Their value lies in arguments that can be tested and revised, not in importing entire seventeenth-century cosmologies into present problems.'
  ],['philosophy-of-mind','logic','philosophy-of-science'],['spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway'],[]),
  section('reading-path','How to compare rationalist systems',[
    'Begin with Descartes’ Discourse on Method and the first six Meditations, keeping separate the certainty of the cogito from the later arguments required to recover God and body. Read Spinoza’s Ethics slowly through definitions, propositions, demonstrations, and scholia; the informal scholia often reveal the practical stakes. Leibniz’s Discourse on Metaphysics and Monadology are compact but should be paired with selected correspondence or the New Essays. Add Conway early enough that mind-body alternatives do not appear to be only Cartesian dualism, Spinozist monism, and Leibnizian monads.',
    'Notice, too, how style carries method: meditation, geometrical demonstration, dialogue, correspondence, and concise theses ask readers to test different relations between certainty, sequence, and objection. Form is part of each rationalist project, not a neutral wrapper.',
    'Keep an argument map for each system: its proposed starting point, its criterion of adequate knowledge, its basic ontology, and the place it gives to contingency and freedom. Then record the strongest objection raised by another early modern thinker. This method reveals why apparently shared commitments lead to incompatible systems, and it prevents geometrical form or deductive ambition from being mistaken for agreement. It also makes Kant’s later intervention intelligible as a response to several failures at once rather than a generic compromise between two camps.',
    'Then organize reading around a shared question. Compare substance, causal interaction, freedom, innate structure, or sufficient reason across the four thinkers and against Locke or Hume. Finish with Kant’s account of synthetic a priori judgment and the categories, asking what he preserves and rejects from each side. A useful checkpoint is whether one can explain both why sensory evidence is indispensable and why a rationalist believes it cannot supply the full structure of knowledge. If rationalism still means “ignoring experience,” return to the arguments rather than adding more labels.'
  ],['rationalism','empiricism','german-idealism'],['descartes','spinoza','leibniz','anne-conway','locke','hume','kant'],['Discourse on Method','Meditations on First Philosophy','Ethics','Monadology','Critique of Pure Reason'])
];

const empiricism:ArticleSection[]=[
  section('overview','Experience as the beginning, not the end, of inquiry',[
    'Empiricism is a family of views emphasizing experience in accounts of knowledge and concepts. Bacon, Locke, Berkeley, and Hume are commonly grouped within the early modern tradition, but they do not share one theory of mind or reality. Bacon designs practices of experimental inquiry; Locke studies the origin and limits of ideas; Berkeley argues that sensible objects are collections of ideas rather than material substances; Hume analyzes causation, self, morality, and religion through impressions, ideas, habit, and sentiment. The central question is how far experience can supply and justify what people claim to know, not whether reasoning should be abandoned.',
    'The textbook contrast with rationalism is useful only after its limits are clear. Empiricists rely on logic, conceptual distinctions, memory, testimony, and assumptions about reliable inquiry. They do not all say that the mind is a passive recording surface. Locke’s reflection makes awareness of mental operations a source of ideas; Berkeley uses abstract argument to criticize matter; Hume describes active habits of association and expectation. Conversely, rationalists use observations. The debate concerns whether significant content or warrant is independent of experience, how general ideas arise from particular encounters, and what conclusions remain justified once the reach of experience is carefully limited.'
  ],['epistemology','rationalism','philosophy-of-science'],['bacon','locke','berkeley','hume'],['Novum Organum','An Essay Concerning Human Understanding','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
  section('historical-development','Experiment, ideas, skepticism, and later inheritances',[
    'Francis Bacon’s early seventeenth-century program attacks idols of thought and proposes organized observation, experiment, comparison, and exclusion. He did not invent experimentation or advocate gathering facts without hypotheses, but he gave institutional and methodological form to a reform of natural inquiry. Locke’s Essay later rejects innate principles and asks how sensation and reflection furnish the materials of thought. Its arguments belong to medicine, politics, religion, and debates about toleration as well as epistemology. Locke seeks measured confidence rather than universal skepticism, distinguishing knowledge from probability and showing why practical life depends on responsible judgment below certainty.',
    'Berkeley accepts that knowledge begins with ideas while denying that an unknowable material substance explains them. Hume pushes empiricist analysis toward questions about causal necessity, induction, personal identity, miracles, and moral sentiment. His skepticism is moderated by the natural beliefs and practices human life cannot discard. Kant credits Hume with disrupting dogmatic metaphysics and argues that experience requires a priori forms and categories; later positivists, pragmatists, and analytic philosophers transform empiricist ambitions through logic, science, and language. Quine challenges the idea that each meaningful statement can be reduced to immediate experience, showing that empiricism survives by revising its own earlier pictures.'
  ],['philosophy-of-science','analytic-philosophy','pragmatism'],['bacon','locke','berkeley','hume','kant','carnap','quine'],['A Treatise Concerning the Principles of Human Knowledge','Critique of Pure Reason','Two Dogmas of Empiricism']),
  section('key-concepts','Impressions, ideas, abstraction, induction, and probability',[
    'Locke distinguishes ideas of sensation from ideas of reflection and argues that complex ideas are formed by combining, comparing, and abstracting simpler materials. This is not a photographic theory of thought: mental operations organize experience, and language introduces further difficulties. Berkeley criticizes abstract ideas when they are treated as images stripped of every particular feature, and he argues that sensible existence consists in being perceived. Hume’s copy principle states that simple ideas derive from corresponding impressions, using that test to challenge terms whose experiential source cannot be found. Each thinker therefore offers a different account of how experience becomes conceptual thought.',
    'Induction exposes empiricism’s central pressure. Observed regularities do not deductively entail that unobserved cases or the future will resemble the past. Hume argues that expectation rests on custom rather than a demonstrative proof of uniformity. Probability and testimony become essential because most responsible belief falls short of certainty. Primary and secondary qualities, nominal and real essences, association of ideas, and the bundle treatment of self provide further tools for analyzing perception and identity. These concepts are not declarations that only immediate sensations exist; they are attempts to explain how a finite mind moves from experience to a structured world of objects, persons, and expectations.'
  ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-mind','philosophy-of-language'],['locke','berkeley','hume'],['An Essay Concerning Human Understanding','A Treatise of Human Nature']),
  section('figures-works','Bacon, Locke, Berkeley, and Hume in context',[
    'Bacon’s Novum Organum links cognitive error to a cooperative method of investigation, although its rhetoric of dominion over nature and its imperial setting require criticism. Locke’s Essay traces ideas, words, knowledge, probability, and the limits of understanding; its account of personal identity distinguishes continuity of consciousness from sameness of substance. His political writings make him central to liberal traditions while raising serious questions about property, colonialism, and exclusion. Empiricism should not isolate his theory of ideas from the practical institutions and conflicts in which standards of evidence mattered.',
    'Berkeley’s Principles and Three Dialogues argue that ordinary sensible objects remain real even if material substance is rejected; his position is immaterialist, not the view that only his private mind exists. Hume’s Treatise and Enquiries examine understanding, passion, morality, religion, and social life. The shorter Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding is often the best entry into causation and induction, while the Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion applies empirical caution to design and providence. Their differences are decisive: Baconian method, Lockean moderate epistemology, Berkeleyan immaterialism, and Humean naturalism cannot be substituted for one slogan about learning from the senses.'
  ],['political-philosophy','philosophy-of-religion','philosophy-of-mind'],['bacon','locke','berkeley','hume'],['Novum Organum','An Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Three Dialogues between Hylas and Philonous','Dialogues Concerning Natural Religion']),
  section('internal-debates','Matter, causation, self, and the reach of skepticism',[
    'Empiricists disagree about what experience supports. Locke accepts material substance while admitting that substance in general is an obscure supposed support of qualities. Berkeley argues that this supposed material substratum is both unnecessary and unintelligible, preserving objects through their ordered perceptibility and divine coordination. Hume treats perceptions as the available contents of mind and questions whether a simple enduring self is encountered beyond a bundle or succession of perceptions. These positions show empiricism generating bold metaphysics as well as caution. Limiting claims to experience does not determine one ontology.',
    'Causation and skepticism create further divisions. Bacon expects disciplined induction to reveal forms and reliable regularities. Locke allows knowledge in some domains and probable judgment in many others. Hume denies that experience presents necessary connection or rationally proves induction, yet he explains why custom produces unavoidable expectations and supports ordinary inquiry. Interpreters dispute whether this is destructive skepticism, mitigated skepticism, or naturalism. Empiricists also argue over abstract ideas, moral knowledge, religious testimony, free will, and whether perception represents external objects or directly constitutes them. The movement’s unity is a recurring demand to show how claims answer to experience, not an agreed catalogue of acceptable beliefs.'
  ],['metaphysics','skepticism','philosophy-of-religion'],['locke','berkeley','hume','bacon'],['An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding']),
  section('neighbors','Rationalism, science, pragmatism, and analytic philosophy',[
    'Rationalism is the obvious neighbor, but reading by shared problems reveals exchange rather than separation. Locke replies to innate-principle arguments; Leibniz writes the New Essays as a sustained response to Locke; Hume criticizes rational accounts of causation while constructing his own reasoned theory of belief. Kant argues that neither sensory receptivity nor conceptual activity alone yields experience. Philosophy of science inherits Baconian experiment and Humean induction but adds models, instruments, probability, explanation, and social organization. No mature science simply reads conclusions off uninterpreted observations.',
    'Pragmatism transforms empiricism by treating experience as active engagement and inquiry rather than a stream of private sensations. Logical empiricists use formal tools to connect scientific language with evidence, while Quine rejects sharp analytic-synthetic and reductionist assumptions and describes beliefs as facing experience in interconnected networks. Philosophy of mind, language, and social epistemology further show that perception is embodied, concept use is learned, and testimony supplies much of what anyone knows. These later developments do not abandon empiricism; they expose why experience must be understood through practices, theories, and communities.'
  ],['rationalism','philosophy-of-science','pragmatism','analytic-philosophy'],['leibniz','kant','carnap','quine','william-james','dewey'],['New Essays on Human Understanding','Two Dogmas of Empiricism']),
  section('misunderstandings','Why empiricism is not raw data without reason',[
    'The first misconception is that empiricists believe only what they personally see. Historical knowledge, science, and ordinary life depend on memory, testimony, inference, and institutions. The philosophical question is how these sources ultimately connect with experience and earn trust. A second misconception is that the mind is always a blank passive slate. Locke’s “white paper” metaphor concerns the absence of innate ideas, while reflection and mental operations actively form complex thought. Berkeley and Hume develop still different accounts. A third mistake is to call any use of evidence empiricism, as if rationalists ignored observation and empiricists possessed a monopoly on responsible inquiry.',
    'Empiricism also does not automatically imply materialism. Berkeley is the clearest counterexample, and Hume is cautious about claims extending beyond perceptions rather than dogmatically materialist. Nor does Hume’s problem of induction tell people to stop predicting or doing science. It identifies the kind of justification prediction does not possess and redirects attention to habit, probability, method, and fallibility. Finally, empiricism is not a finished seventeenth-century school. Its later transformations in pragmatism, logical empiricism, naturalized epistemology, and philosophy of science show a continuing argument about how evidence constrains theory.'
  ],['empiricism','rationalism','philosophy-of-science'],['locke','berkeley','hume'],[]),
  section('modern-relevance','Evidence, data, expertise, and uncertain decisions',[
    'Empiricist problems are visible whenever data must support a conclusion beyond the observations collected. Clinical trials, climate models, polling, machine learning, and policy evaluation all depend on sampling, measurement, background assumptions, and inductive projection. More data does not automatically remove bias if categories, instruments, or incentives are poorly designed. Hume’s problem explains why prediction remains fallible; Bacon’s attention to organized error explains why institutions matter; Locke’s treatment of probability shows why responsible action cannot wait for certainty. Empiricism at its best is a discipline of revisability, not a promise that facts interpret themselves.',
    'Digital life also raises questions about testimony and experience. People know most scientific and historical facts through others, while repetition and visibility can mimic independent confirmation. Social epistemology extends empiricist concerns toward expertise, credibility, and distributed inquiry. Artificial intelligence systems trained on past data intensify the issue of induction under changing conditions: patterns may fail when environments or populations shift. The tradition’s lasting lesson is double. Claims must remain answerable to experience, but experience becomes evidence only through concepts, comparisons, causal reasoning, and communities capable of detecting error.'
  ],['epistemology','philosophy-of-science','political-philosophy'],['bacon','hume','locke'],[]),
  section('reading-path','A route through experience and its limits',[
    'Begin with Bacon’s discussion of the idols and selected examples from the Novum Organum, asking how method tries to correct both individual bias and unorganized observation. Read Locke’s Essay selections on the origin of ideas, primary and secondary qualities, personal identity, words, and the degrees of assent. Then use Berkeley’s Principles or Three Dialogues to see that empiricist premises can support immaterialism rather than common-sense materialism. Hume’s Enquiry should follow, especially the sections on the origin of ideas, causal inference, probability, liberty and necessity, and miracles.',
    'The comparison should also identify what could revise the claim. An appeal to experience that cannot specify possible correction has lost the fallibilist discipline that gives empiricism its enduring force.',
    'For a final exercise, take one contemporary evidence claim and separate observation, measurement, background theory, testimony, and inductive projection. Ask which element each historical empiricist could explain and where that account would fail. This turns the tradition into a diagnostic toolkit without pretending that seventeenth- or eighteenth-century psychology can simply be adopted today. It also shows why later empiricisms became more social, probabilistic, and theory-aware while retaining the demand that inquiry remain corrigible by experience.',
    'Compare each thinker on one question instead of treating the sequence as increasingly skeptical. What does experience contain? How are general concepts formed? What justifies belief in objects, causes, or selves? Then read Kant’s response to Hume and a later text such as James on experience, Carnap on confirmation, or Quine’s Two Dogmas. Pair philosophical arguments with a scientific case involving measurement or theory change. A reader understands empiricism when “experience matters” has become a precise set of questions about evidence, conceptual structure, inference, and correction rather than a slogan.'
  ],['empiricism','rationalism','philosophy-of-science'],['bacon','locke','berkeley','hume','kant','william-james','carnap','quine'],['Novum Organum','An Essay Concerning Human Understanding','Three Dialogues between Hylas and Philonous','An Enquiry Concerning Human Understanding','Two Dogmas of Empiricism'])
];

